10.body: The following grading scheme will be used to assess your report: Introduction ( 5 marks ) A brief introduction to the problem. Methods ( 20 marks ) Describe the data and the study site. Description of the analysis approach. Include the Python script that you used to help document your approach the the change detection analysis. Be sure to use at least two different change detection approaches . Describe the approaches that you used to address the problem. For example, what pre-processing techniques , if any, did you need use? Did you use pre- or post-classification approaches, or perhaps a combination of both? In other words, exactly what techniques did you select? Be sure to provide justifications for the approaches that you chose. What are some of the advantages and limitations of the approach that you used? Results – Graphics ( 10 marks ) Results of analysis (images, maps, graphs, and/or tables where relevant). Results – Documentation ( 20 marks ) Interpretation of results. Statement of limitations of your results (i.e. because of limitations of your methodology). General presentation ( 10 marks ) Neat and concise reporting Spelling and grammar (be sure to proofread your work) Organization (report is well laid-out using appropriate sections) Consistent in-text citations and reference list. The total is 65 marks .

10.title: Grading the Final Report

2.body: The learning objectives for this lab assignment include the following: To learn about the issues related to performing a change detection analysis on multi-date multi-spectral satellite imagery. To design and implement a small research project, research information on how to address the assigned problem, and to apply a customized solution. To bring together several of the concepts that you have learned throughout this course in a single assignment.
2.title: Learning objectives

3.body: I assume that, at this point in the course, you have a good working knowledge of the Whitebox Workflows and general image processing techniques. Therefore, this final lab is more free-form than the previous assignments. You will be given some background information on what the general topics and requirements are for the lab, but it will be up to you as to how to carry out the analysis. One of the fundamental skills that you will need to take from this course is how to search for and find the information that you need to solve a remote-sensing problem. In this assignment, you are asked to complete a land-use/land-cover change detection analysis for the nearly 21 years between July 6, 2001 and June 16, 2022. You have been provided with cropped Landsat 7 (2001 scene) and Landsat 9 (2022 scene) imagery for the area of interest on the CourseLink site. These data comprise of the blue, green, red, and near-infrared bands of a Landsat 7 (bands 1, 2, 3, and 4 respectively) and Landsat 9 (bands 2, 3, 4, and 5 respectively). Both image datasets are Level-2 ( atmospherically corrected to surface reflectance ) scenes (path 18, row 30) that cover part of the Greater Toronto Area (GTA), Hamilton, Guelph, Cambridge, and Kitchener-Waterloo. Note that the image metadata, providing details of the image acquisition, is also distributed along with the imagery. This is the same area (but different images) that we have been using for the lab assignments throughout the semester. As such, you should have a good level of familiarity with the data and the study area. I have provided you with a cropped versions of the original full-scene data set in order to reduce the files to a manageable sizes. I have also performed a percent contrast stretch (PCS) on each band, clipping the lower and upper 0.5% of the image histogram. For this assignment, you are a remote sensing consultant, hired by me. Don't get too excited, I’m hiring you to work for free ! I am an urban planner tasked with developing a plan for Ontario's growing population over the next decade. As such, I am interested in documenting and evaluating the urban expansion that has taken place in the southern Ontario over the recent past, such that I may work with municipalities to plan for the anticipated population growth in their communities. Information about the previous development in the region will allow me to better characterize the capacity for growth in each community. Therefore, I am interested in documenting the recent development in the GTA and surrounding communities and have contracted you, a remote-sensing specialist working for a private consulting company, to aid with documenting urban expansion over the 21-year period between image acquisition dates. I am particularly interested in documenting which areas of the region have experienced the greatest changes (urban expansion into surrounding rural areas) and documenting what type of urban development these past changes have been associated with (e.g. commercial/industrial growth, suburban development, etc.). My primary concern is to document expansion of residential neighbourhoods . To answer these questions you will have to perform automated change detection analysis on the provided satellite imagery. It is up to you to research how to go about conducting this analysis but I have provided you with a short list of resources to help guide you. You should supplement this list with any additional resources on change detection analysis that you can find during your research, and of course, with the lecture slides on this topic.
3.title: Introduction

4.body: As you begin your analysis you should note a few things about the data: The scenes are not perfectly cloud free and the 2001 image in particular has several thick clouds (and their associated cloud shadows) in the upper-right corner of the image. This is actually why I cropped the Toronto downtown area out of the raw imagery; it was too heavily cloud covered for useful analysis. The presence of this cloud cover means that some apparent 'change' may be the difference between cloud/no-cloud between dates. Be aware of this 'uninteresting change' as you interpret your results. The Enhanced Thematic Mapper Plus (ETM+) imaging sensor of Landsat 7 and the Operational Land Imager 2 (OLI-2) imaging sensor of Landsat 9 differ in significant ways. This is why I only provided you with four corresponding bands (blue, green, red, and NIR) from each raw data set; these are the bands that have equivalents between the two sensors. However, the correspondence is not perfect. You will note, if you click on the Landsat 7 and Landsat 9 info page links above, that the spectral ranges of each corresponding bands are not exactly the same. For example, for Landsat 7 the red band (band 3) has a spectral range from 0.63 - 0.69 µm, while the Landsat 9 red-band (band 4) has a range from 0.64 - 0.67 µm. This small difference will have some minor implications for the change detection, since each band is not detecting precisely the same range of wavelengths. The band designation of the two data sets are offset by one. That is L7 B1 = L9 B2, L7 B2 = L9 B3, etc. This is because Landsat 7 does not have an equivalent to the Landsat 9 band 1 (aerosol). The two scenes are not anniversary dates, i.e., the 2022 imagery was taken nearly 3 weeks earlier in the growing season than the 2001 imagery. Now, for the most part, we are disinterested in changes that are associated with the seasonal changes of crops and, of course, in the differences caused by differing crop types in a field (i.e., crop rotations). Instead, we are interested in urban changes and so this use of non-anniversary dates is likely acceptable for our application. But it is something that you should be aware of and consider when interpreting your results. A field that changes from corn in 2001 to soy beans in 2022 is not as interesting as an agricultural field that changes into single-family housing.
4.title: Things to consider

5.body: Prepare a short report of no more than 4 to 5 pages (not including maps and references) documenting the data and procedure you followed, as well as the results of your analysis. Your final report should include an introduction , a brief description of your methodology , the results of your analyses, a section describing the limitations of your methodology, your recommendations , and a references cited (see the Marking Format, below). Remember, this is a consultant's client report and we are expecting a level of professionalism. Marks will be assigned for originality, demonstration of sound remote sensing principles and practice, and innovation. The methodology section of your final report must include WbW-based Python script(s) that documents your approaches to performing the change detection analysis and describe any image pre-processing techniques that you used.

7.title: Change Detection Analysis Resources

8.body: When you download the data for this lab exercise, notice that a sub-directory called Change detection resources is also created. In this folder, you will find a number of resources to help guide you through your change detection analysis. Jensen, J.R. (2016) Introductory Digital Image Processing , Chapter 12. This is a set of lecture slides associated with Jensen's excellent digital image processing textbook. It provides quite detailed information and contains a wealth of background material on the topic of change detection analysis. Mas, J.F. (1999) Monitoring land-cover changes: a comparison of change detection techniques, International Journal of Remote Sensing , 20(1): 139-152. This is an excellent journal article comparing some of the common techniques for performing change detection analysis. I'd certainly recommend reading this source carefully. Mather, P.M. and Koch, M. (2011) Computer Processing of Remotely-Sensed Images. Chapter 6 Image Transforms, Section 6.8 Change Detection pp. 187-195. And a short list of some other useful web resources: Natural Resources Canada (NRCan) (2013) Land Use Change (Rural / Urban) , online resource: https://www.nrcan.gc.ca/earth-sciences/geomatics/satellite-imagery-air-photos/satellite-imagery-products/educational-resources/9357. Jennifer Pontius (2020) Change detection , online resource: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=r7koPp0uJw8.
8.breadcrumbs: Change Detection Analysis Resources » Readings and background material
8.title: Readings and background material

9.body: The Whitebox Workflows library contains several tools that can be useful in workflows for performing change detection analysis on two-date, multi-spectral satellite imagery. Some of the more common tools include, but are not limited to: change_vector_analysis cross_tabulation image_regression k_means_clustering knn_classification min_dist_classification modified_k_means_clustering normalized_difference_index parallelepiped_classification principal_component_analysis random_forest_classification svm_classification write_function_memory_insertion And, of course, there are the raster mathematical operations of image differencing (subtraction) and ratioing (division). Please refer to the Whitebox Workflows for Python User Manual for details on the operation of each of the tools.
